<title>NETHERLANDS: Clinton sidesteps EMU question at US-EU summit.</title>
<headline>Clinton sidesteps EMU question at US-EU summit.</headline>
<dateline>THE HAGUE 1997-05-28</dateline>
<text>
<p>U.S. President Bill Clinton on Wednesday sidestepped a question about whether Washington was keen to see the European Union adopt a single currency, saying only that European integration was good for everyone.</p>
<p>At a news conference following the twice-yearly U.S.-EU summit, Clinton said Washington remained committed to seeing Europe brought closer together.</p>
<p>&quot;We are not only not threatened by that, we are excited about it, he said.</p>
<p>But Clinton would not be drawn on whether the EU's planned single currency, due to be introduced initially on January 1, 1999, was welcomed by Washington.</p>
<p>&quot;The decision to do that and the mechanics (of it) are a matter for the Union,&quot; he said, adding that it would be inappropriate for him to comment further.</p>
</text>
